The article is a Presidential Proclamation from April 28, 2009, titled "National Equal Pay Day, 2009." The proclamation highlights the ongoing issue of pay inequity for women in the United States, despite the passage of the Equal Pay Act 46 years prior. It emphasizes the importance of ending wage discrimination and the negative impact it has on women and families. The proclamation mentions the Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009, which extends the timeline for filing complaints of pay discrimination, as well as the establishment of the White House Council on Women and Girls. The proclamation calls for collective action from businesses, community organizations, and individuals to ensure equal pay for both women and men. It concludes by proclaiming April 28, 2009, as National Equal Pay Day and urging American men and women, as well as employers, to commit to equal pay for equal work.